{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17565331","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17565331"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:25:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:25:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17368"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17368","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17368"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.32,0.33,0.16,0.12,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10058"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89981"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10058","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10058"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17368"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74139"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"409"},{"type":"tags","id":"1058"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"2838"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23551"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30655"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35685"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89981","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/89981"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department after being stung by a bee while gardening 15 minutes ago. She has developed generalised urticaria, difficulty breathing, and feels lightheaded. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She has never been stung by a bee before.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears distressed. Her pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 85/50 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. She has widespread urticaria and facial swelling. The bee stinger is visible in her right forearm. A nurse is urgently retrieving intramuscular adrenaline.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate method to remove the bee stinger?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pull out with forceps","Scrape sideways with credit card","Leave in place until after initial resuscitation","Apply ice pack first then remove","Squeeze base of stinger with fingers"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with anaphylaxis to a bee sting, characterised by acute onset respiratory symptoms, hypotension, and widespread urticaria. While immediate intramuscular adrenaline is crucial for treating anaphylaxis, proper removal of the bee stinger is also important to prevent continued envenomation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScraping sideways with a credit card\u003C/strong\u003E or similar flat edge is the recommended method for removing a bee stinger. This technique minimises the risk of squeezing more venom from the venom sac into the wound. The scraping motion should be performed parallel to the skin surface.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulling out with forceps\u003C/strong\u003E risks squeezing the venom sac and injecting more venom into the wound. This in turn would increase the amount of antigen in the body and perpetuate the allergic reaction. The mechanical grip of forceps or tweezers can compress the venom sac before removal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESqueezing the base of the stinger\u003C/strong\u003E with fingers is incorrect for the same reason - it may force more venom into the wound, sustaining the exposure to the antigen causing the reaction. Additionally, touching the stinger with bare hands could potentially cause a sting to the person providing assistance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EApplying ice pack first\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary and would delay removal of the stinger. The priority is to remove the stinger as quickly as possible to prevent further envenomation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeaving in place\u003C/strong\u003E until after initial resuscitation is incorrect. While treating anaphylaxis is the priority, the stinger should be removed as soon as possible as it continues to pump venom for 45-60 seconds after the sting. Stinger removal can be delegated to another healthcare worker while simultaneously initiating resuscitation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter stinger removal and administration of adrenaline, ongoing monitoring is required. The patient should be observed for at least 4-8 hours due to the risk of biphasic reactions. They should be prescribed an adrenaline auto-injector and referred to an immunologist for consideration of venom immunotherapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Bee stings should be scraped off sideways rather than pulled or squeezed to avoid injecting more venom","Anaphylaxis requires immediate intramuscular adrenaline as first-line treatment","The presence of respiratory or cardiovascular symptoms indicates anaphylaxis rather than a local reaction"],"references":["Golden DBK, Moffitt JE, Nicklas RA, et al. Stinging insect hypersensitivity: A practice parameter update 2011. J Allergy Clin Immunol. 2011;127(4):852\u2013854. Available at: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jaci.2010.12.231","Sicherer SH, Simons FER; Section on Allergy and Immunology. Epinephrine for first-aid management of anaphylaxis. Pediatrics. 2017;139(3):e20164006. Available at: https://doi.org/10.1542/peds.2016-4006","Visscher PK, Vetter RS. Removing bee stings: Speed matters, method does not. Ann Emerg Med. 1996;27(4):549\u2013551. Available at: https://doi.org/10.1016/s0196-0644(96)70272-0"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74139"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17368"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74139","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74139"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-11T15:02:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-14T12:12:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10058"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89981"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"27","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/27"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc77","name":"Occupational/Environmental Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonym